{"title_page": "Gurung people", "text_new": "{{see also|Gurung (surname)|Gurung Dharma|Gurung language}}\n \n{{refimprove|date=July 2015}}\nThe '''Gurung people''', also called '''Tamu'''(\u0f4f\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f74), are an ethnic group from different parts of Nepal. They are one of the main Gurkha tribes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?url=http://www.his.com/~mesas/articles/OCR_Ragsdale_CNAS.pdf|title=Ethnohistory of Gurung People|accessdate=5 June 2013}}</ref> They are densely populated in Manang, Mustang, Kaski, Lamjung, Gorkha, Parbat and Shyanja district. According to 2011 Census, the total population of Gurung is 5, 22,641.\n<br />\n\n== History ==\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group            = Gurung people\n| image            = <!-- Deleted image removed:  [[File:Gurung woman performing \"Ghatu\".jpg]] -->\n| caption          = Gurung woman in traditional attire.\n| languages        = [[Gurung language|Gurung]] (Tamu kwyi) and [[Manang language]], [[Nepali language|Nepali]]\n| religions        = Majority [[Buddhism]] and Hinduism<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/93185530/Social-Composition-of-Nepal-Caste-Ethnicity-amp-Religion |title=Chapter 3. Social composition of the Population: Caste/Ethnicity and Religion in Nepal |author=Dr. Dilli Ram Dahal |publisher=[[Government of Nepal]], Central Bureau of Statistics |date=2002-12-30 |accessdate=2013-12-05}}</ref>\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| related_groups   = \n}}\nTheir traditional religious scripture is known as Pye-ta Lhu-ta which contains oral accounts of their traditional history.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Macfarlane, Alan.|url=http://worldcat.org/oclc/841774183|title=Gurungs of Nepal : a guide to the Gurungs|date=1992|publisher=Ratna Pustak Bhandar|oclc=841774183}}</ref> According to their legend, the Gurung were a wandering tribe that traversed west across Tibet prior to their entry into Mustang. Their Tibetan Sojourn pre-dates the introduction of Buddhism there in the 7<sup>th</sup> century as the Gurung religious traditions are basically animistic. They celebrate their feasts and festivals and carry out the ceremonies and practices related to worship, birth, death and marriage in accordance with the Bon and Buddhist religion. Losar is the main and biggest festival of Gurung, observed according to the ancient calendar of western Tibet. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indigenousvoice.com/en/indigenous-peoples/4/gurung.html|title=Indigenous Peoples -Gurung|website=www.indigenousvoice.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n[[File:Gurung girls during gurung losar.jpg|alt=|thumb|Gurung girls]]\n<br />\n\n==Geographical distribution==\nAt the time of the [[2011 Nepal census]], 522,641 people (2.0% of the population of Nepal) identified as Gurung. The frequency of the Gurung people was higher than national average in the following districts: [[Manang District, Nepal|Manang]] (52.4%), [[Lamjung District|Lamjung]] (31.3%), [[Mustang District|Mustang]] (21.4%), [[Gorkha District|Gorkha]] (19.7%), [[Kaski District|Kaski]] (16.6%), [[Tanahun District|Tanahun]] (11.5%), [[Syangja District|Syangja]] (9.0%), [[Dolpa District|Dolpa]] (7.1%), [[Chitwan District|Chitwan]] (6.8%), [[Dhading District|Dhading]] (5.5%), [[Sankhuwasabha District|Sankhuwasabha]] (5.4%), [[Taplejung District|Taplejung]] (4.6%), [[Parbat District|Parbat]] (3.7%), [[Rasuwa District|Rasuwa]] (3.1%), [[Tehrathum District|Tehrathum]] (2.9%), [[Ilam District|Ilam]] (2.9%), [[Kathmandu District|Kathmandu]] (2.6%), [[Nawalparasi District|Nawalparasi]] (2.4%) and [[Rupandehi District|Rupandehi]] (2.0%).<ref>[https://cbs.gov.np/wp-content/upLoads/2018/12/Volume05Part02.pdf 2011 Nepal Census, Social Characteristics Tables]</ref>  \n\n==Religion==\nPriestly practitioners of the Gurung Dharma include Ghyabri (Klehpri), Pachyu (Paju), and Bon Lamas.<ref name=Fuehrer>{{cite book|title=Tribal populations and cultures of the Indian subcontinent |volume=2 |issue=7 |first=Christoph |last=von F\u00fcrer-Haimendorf |authorlink=Christoph von F\u00fcrer-Haimendorf |pages=137\u20138 |publisher=[[Brill Publishers]] |year=1985 |ISBN=90-04-07120-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aRSOnRfPAq0C&pg=PA137 |accessdate=2011-04-02}}</ref> Shamanistic elements among the Gurungs remain strong and most Gurungs often embrace Buddhist and B\u00f6n rituals in communal activities.<ref name=Latham>{{cite book|title=Descriptive Ethnology |volume=I |author=[[Robert Gordon Latham]]|year=1859 |publisher=John Van Voorst, Paternoster Row |location=London |pages=80\u201382}}</ref><ref name=Mumford>{{cite book|title=Himalayan Dialogue: Tibetan Lamas and Gurung Shamans in Nepal |author=Mumford, Stanley Royal |pages=30\u201332 |year=1989 |publisher=University of Wisconsin Press |location=[[Madison, Wisconsin]] |isbn=0-299-11984-X}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 2011 census, the majority of the Gurungs practise either Buddhism (62.72%) or Hinduism (32.18%). However, a small minority practises the original Bonpo religion (2.32%).\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Gurung language]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book\n|title= Nepal, the Living Heritage: Environment and Culture\n|author = P. T. Sherpa Kerung, Susan H\u00f6ivik\n|year = 2002\n|publisher = Kathmandu Environmental Education Project\n|location = University of Michigan}}\n*{{cite book\n|title= The Land of the Gurkhas, or, The Himalayan Kingdom of Nepal\n|author = William Brook Northey\n|year = 1998\n|publisher = Asian Educational Services\n|isbn = 81-206-1329-5}}\n*{{cite book\n|title= The Gurungs, Thunder of Himal: A Cross Cultural Study of a Nepalese Ethnic Group\n|author = Mur\u0101r\u012bpras\u0101da Regm\u012b\n|year = 1990\n|publisher = Nirala Publications\n|location = University of Michigan}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--========================({{No More Links}})============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA  |\n    | IS NOT A COLLECTION