{"title_page": "Fort Nassau (North River)", "text_new": "{{about|the fort in New York|the one in New Jersey|Fort Nassau (South River)|other settlements|Fort Nassau (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n| name =  Fort Nassau\n| partof = [[New Netherland]]\n| location = [[Albany, New York]]\n| image =\n| caption =\n| map_type =\n| coordinates = \n| type = [[Fort]]\n| code =\n| height =\n| controlledby =\n| open_to_public =\n| condition =\n| built = 1614\n| builder = [[Hendrick Christiaensen]]\n| used =\n| materials = Wooden structure<br/>surrounded by earthenworks\n| demolished = 1618\n| battles =\n| events = First Dutch fort<br/>in [[North America]]\n| current_commander =\n| past_commanders = [[Jacob Eelkens]]\n| garrison = 10 or 12 men\n| occupants = [[Republic of the Seven United Netherlands|Dutch]] traders and soldiers\n}}\n{{New Netherland}}\n\n'''Fort Nassau''' (a.k.a. '''Fort van Nassouwen''') was the first [[Dutch Republic|Dutch]] settlement in [[North America]], located beside the \"[[North River (Hudson River)|North River]]\" (the modern [[Hudson River|Hudson]]) within present-day [[Albany, New York]], in the United States. The ''[[factorij]]'' was a small fortification which served as a trading post and warehouse.\n\n==History==\n[[Henry Hudson]] explored what would be known as the [[Hudson River]] for the Dutch in 1609, including [[Castle Island (New York)|Castle Island]] which was at the center of [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] [[fur]] trading routes from the interior.<ref name=Tour>{{cite web | title = A Virtual Tour of New Netherland: Fort Nassau |url= http://www.newnetherlandinstitute.org/history-and-heritage/digital-exhibitions/a-tour-of-new-netherland/albany/fort-nassau/ | publisher = New Netherland Institute}}</ref> [[Hendrick Christiaensen]] chose Castle Island to build Fort Nassau, in 1614 or 1615 as a dual warehouse and military defense structure and named the fort in honor of the [[stadtholder]] of the [[Republic of the Seven United Netherlands|United Netherlands]], who was of the [[House of Orange-Nassau]]. Nineteenth and early-twentieth century historians claimed that around 1540, French fur traders built a stone \"castle\" or fortified trading post on Castle Island in the location where Fort Nassau was later built.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=XNU0AAAAIAAJ&pg=PR27&hl=en#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Albany Chronicles'', J. B. Lyon Company, Albany, NY, 1906]</ref> However, modern scholars have found no evidence to support this claim.<ref>[https://newyorkhistoryblog.org/2014/09/debunking-the-french-fort-on-albanys-castle-island/ \"Debunking The 'French Fort' On Albany's Castle Island\"], Stephen T. McErleane, 2014.</ref> Fort Nassau was the first Dutch settlement in [[North America]].<ref>{{cite web | title = The Dutch Settlements in North America | author = Ramerini, Marco | url = http://www.colonialvoyage.com/newnether.html | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100722013842/http://www.colonialvoyage.com/newnether.html | archivedate = 2010-07-22 }}</ref> Jacob Eelkens became commander on Christiaensen's death in 1616.<ref name=Chronicles/>\n\nIn 1617 a [[freshet]] damaged the fort to such an extent that it was abandoned and rebuilt on more secure ground at the [[mouth (river)|mouth]] of the Normans [[Kill (body of water)|Kill]] (called the ''Tawasentha'' by the natives) with the Hudson River. This new fortification was built by Eelkens on a [[topographic prominence|prominence]] called ''Tawass-gunshee'' by the natives. Once the new fort was completed, the Dutch completed their first treaty with natives of North America.{{sfn|Brodhead, p. 81}} In 1618 a freshet destroyed the new fort, and it was abandoned for good.<ref name=Chronicles>{{cite book | title = Albany Chronicles: A History of the City Arranged Chronologically | publisher = J.B. Lyon Company | author = Reynolds, Cuyler | url =  https://books.google.com/books?id=XNU0AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA18&dq=fort+nassau+albany&hl=en&ei=H_NlTMSVNMiKnQfJo9ilDA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false | year = 1906}}</ref>\n\nIn 1624, the Dutch built [[Fort Orange (New Netherland)|Fort Orange]] nearby.\n\n==Geography==\nFort Nassau was built on what is now called [[Westerlo Island]] and was formerly called Castle Island. The island was part of the [[Town (New York)|town]] of [[Bethlehem, New York|Bethlehem]] until 1926 when it was annexed to the city of Albany.<ref>{{cite web | title = Cutting Ice: Big Business in Bethlehem | publisher = Town of Bethlehem | url = http://www.townofbethlehem.org/pages/history/historyArticlesIceCutting.asp | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20101006020426/http://www.townofbethlehem.org/pages/history/historyArticlesIceCutting.asp | archivedate = 2010-10-06 }}</ref>  It has been part of the [[Port of Albany-Rensselaer]] since 1932.<ref>{{cite web | title = Castle Island | publisher = New York State Museum Colonial Albany Social History Project | url = http://www.nysm.nysed.gov/albany/na/castle.html | date = 2001-12-11}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nFort Nassau was a {{convert|36|ft|m|adj=on}} long by {{convert|26|ft|m|adj=on}} wide building enclosed by a {{convert|58|ft|m|adj=on}} square stockade surrounded by an {{convert|18|ft|m|adj=on}} wide [[moat]]. The fort was defended by two large [[cannon]] and eleven [[swivel gun]]s. The fort was garrisoned by 10-12 men.<ref name=History>{{cite book|\nurl=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=13f13lTfG4AC | year = 1853 | page = 55 | publisher = Harper & Brothers | title = History of the State of New York: First Period 1609-1664 | author = Brodhead, John Romeyn}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Two Row Wampum Treaty]]\n*[[Fort Nassau (South River)]]\n*[[Fortifications of New Netherland]]\n*[[History of Albany, New York]]\n*[[New Netherland settlements]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.albany.edu/museum/wwwmuseum/tantillo/trading.html The Trading House 1615] Artist Len Tantillo's vision of what Fort Nassau may have looked like\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|title=Forts of [[Albany, New York]]<br/>Fort Nassau | before=French fort<br/>1540 | after=[[Fort Orange (New Netherland)|Fort Orange]]<br/>1623-1676 | years=1614-1618}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Albany, New York}}\n{{Capital District}}\n\n{{coord missing|Capital District}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Forts of New Netherland|Nassau]]\n[[Category:Colonial forts in New York (state)|Nassau]]\n[[Category:1614 establishments in the Dutch Empire]]\n[[Category:History of Albany, New York]]\n[[Category:Dutch-American culture in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Dutch place names in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the fortress in New York|the one in New Jersey|Fort Nassau (South River)|other settlements around the world with the same name|Fort Nassau (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n| name =  Fort Nassau\n| partof = [[New Netherland]]\n| location = [[Albany, New York]]\n| image =\n| caption =\n| map_type =\n| coordinates = \n| type = [[Fort]]\n| code =\n| height =\n| controlledby =\n| open_to_public =\n| condition =\n| built = 1614\n| builder = [[Hendrick Christiaensen]]\n| used =\n| materials = Wooden structure<br/>surrounded by earthenworks\n| demolished = 1618\n| battles =\n| events = First Dutch fort<br/>in [[North America]]\n| current_commander =\n| past_commanders = [[Jacob Eelkens]]\n| garrison = 10 or 12 men\n| occupants = [[Republic of the Seven United Netherlands|Dutch]] traders and soldiers\n}}\n{{New Netherland}}\n\n'''Fort Nassau''' (a.k.a. '''Fort van Nassouwen''') was the first [[Dutch Republic|Dutch]] settlement in [[North America]], located beside the \"[[North River (Hudson River)|North River]]\" (the modern [[Hudson River|Hudson]]) within present-day [[Albany, New York|Albany]], [[New York (state)|New York]], in the [[United States]]. The ''[[factorij]]'' was a small fortification which served as a trading post and warehouse.\n\n==History==\n[[Henry Hudson]] explored what would be known as the [[Hudson River]] for the Dutch in 1609, including [[Castle Island (New York)|Castle Island]] which was at the center of [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] [[fur]] trading routes from the interior.<ref name=Tour>{{cite web | title = A Virtual Tour of New Netherland: Fort Nassau |url= http://www.newnetherlandinstitute.org/history-and-heritage/digital-exhibitions/a-tour-of-new-netherland/albany/fort-nassau/ | publisher = New Netherland Institute}}</ref> [[Hendrick Christiaensen]] chose Castle Island to build Fort Nassau, in 1614 or 1615 as a dual warehouse and military defense structure and named the fort in honor of the [[stadtholder]] of the [[Republic of the Seven United Netherlands|United Netherlands]], who was of the [[House of Orange-Nassau]]. Nineteenth and early-twentieth century historians claimed that around 1540, French fur traders built a stone \"castle\" or fortified trading post on Castle Island in the location where Fort Nassau was later built.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=XNU0AAAAIAAJ&pg=PR27&hl=en#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Albany Chronicles'', J. B. Lyon Company, Albany, NY, 1906]</ref> However, modern scholars have found no evidence to support this claim.<ref>[https://newyorkhistoryblog.org/2014/09/debunking-the-french-fort-on-albanys-castle-island/] \"Debunking The \u2018French Fort\u2019 On Albany\u2019s Castle Island,\" Stephen T McErleane, 2014.</ref> Fort Nassau was the first Dutch settlement in [[North America]].<ref>{{cite web | title = The Dutch Settlements in North America | author = Ramerini, Marco | url = http://www.colonialvoyage.com/newnether.html | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100722013842/http://www.colonialvoyage.com/newnether.html | archivedate = 2010-07-22 }}</ref> Jacob Eelkens became commander on Christiaensen's death in 1616.<ref name=Chronicles/>\n\nIn 1617 a [[freshet]] damaged the fort to such an extent that it was abandoned and rebuilt on more secure ground at the [[mouth (river)|mouth]] of the Normans [[Kill (body of water)|Kill]] (called the ''Tawasentha'' by the natives) with the Hudson River. This new fortification was built by Eelkens on a [[topographic prominence|prominence]] called ''Tawass-gunshee'' by the natives. Once the new fort was completed, the Dutch completed their first treaty with natives of North America.{{sfn|Brodhead, p. 81}} In 1618 a freshet destroyed the new fort, and it was abandoned for good.<ref name=Chronicles>{{cite book | title = Albany Chronicles: A History of the City Arranged Chronologically | publisher = J.B. Lyon Company | author = Reynolds, Cuyler | url =  https://books.google.com/books?id=XNU0AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA18&dq=fort+nassau+albany&hl=en&ei=H_NlTMSVNMiKnQfJo9ilDA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false | year = 1906}}</ref>\n\nIn 1624, the Dutch built [[Fort Orange (New Netherland)|Fort Orange]] nearby.\n\n==Geography==\nFort Nassau was built on what is now called [[Westerlo Island]] and was formerly called Castle Island. The island was part of the [[Town (New York)|town]] of [[Bethlehem, New York|Bethlehem]] until 1926 when it was annexed to the city of Albany.<ref>{{cite web | title = Cutting Ice: Big Business in Bethlehem | publisher = Town of Bethlehem | url = http://www.townofbethlehem.org/pages/history/historyArticlesIceCutting.asp | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20101006020426/http://www.townofbethlehem.org/pages/history/historyArticlesIceCutting.asp | archivedate = 2010-10-06 }}</ref>  It has been part of the [[Port of Albany-Rensselaer]] since 1932.<ref>{{cite web | title = Castle Island | publisher = New York State Museum Colonial Albany Social History Project | url = http://www.nysm.nysed.gov/albany/na/castle.html | date = 2001-12-11}}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nFort Nassau was a {{convert|36|ft|m|adj=on}} long by {{convert|26|ft|m|adj=on}} wide building enclosed by a {{convert|58|ft|m|adj=on}} square stockade surrounded by an {{convert|18|ft|m|adj=on}} wide [[moat]]. The fort was defended by two large [[cannon]] and eleven [[swivel gun]]s. The fort was garrisoned by 10-12 men.<ref name=History>{{cite book|\nurl=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=13f13lTfG4AC | year = 1853 | page = 55 | publisher = Harper & Brothers | title = History of the State of New York: First Period 1609-1664 | author = Brodhead, John Romeyn}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Two Row Wampum Treaty]]\n*[[Fort Nassau (South River)]]\n*[[Fortifications of New Netherland]]\n*[[History of Albany, New York]]\n*[[New Netherland settlements]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.albany.edu/museum/wwwmuseum/tantillo/trading.html The Trading House 1615] Artist Len Tantillo's vision of what Fort Nassau may have looked like\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|title=Forts of [[Albany, New York]]<br/>Fort Nassau | before=French fort<br/>1540 | after=[[Fort Orange (New Netherland)|Fort Orange]]<br/>1623-1676 | years=1614-1618}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Albany, New York}}\n{{Capital District}}\n\n{{coord missing|Capital District}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Forts of New Netherland|Nassau]]\n[[Category:Colonial forts in New York (state)|Nassau]]\n[[Category:1614 establishments in the Dutch Empire]]\n[[Category:History of Albany, New York]]\n[[Category:Dutch-American culture in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Dutch place names in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Station1", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fort_Nassau_(North_River)"}
{"title_page": "Valery Klimov (violinist)", "text_new": "{{no footnotes|date=October 2008}}\n'''Valeri Klimov''' (born October 16, 1931) is a [[Russia]]n violinist.\n\n==Biography==\nKlimov was born in [[Kiev]] (then in the [[Soviet Union]], now in [[Ukraine]]). He began to study music under the guidance of his father - conductor and teacher [[Alexander Ignatievich Klimov]]. From the age of 7 he studied (with a break for evacuation in Stalingrad during the war) at the Odessa Music Boarding School for Gifted Children with [[Pyotr Stolyarsky]] (now called the [[School of Stolyarsky]] (for gifted children)), Starting in 1945, he studied with B.Z. Mordkovich. In 1949 he performed public concerts featuring repertoire by [[Alexander Glazunov]], [[W.A. Mozart]] and [[Felix Mendelssohn]]. There he met [[David Oistrakh]].\n\nIn 1951 he entered the Kiev Conservatory. P.I. Tchaikovsky (now the [[Petro Tchaikovsky National Music Academy of Ukraine]]), where he studied under B.S. Fishman. After a year of study, he was transferred to the [[Moscow Conservatory]] in the studio of [[David Oistrakh]] (graduated with honors in 1956, graduate school in 1959 under his tutelage).\n\nIn 1955, he took sixth place in what is now known as the [[Long\u2013Thibaud\u2013Crespin Competition]]. A year later, he became the winner of the J. Slavik and F. Ond\u0159icek violin competition, but his main success was brought by the 1st [[International Tchaikovsky Competition]] (1958), where he won the gold medal in the violin category.\n\nSince 1957, he has been a soloist of the Moscow Philharmonic Society. He performed in the USSR and abroad. He performed with the largest orchestras in the world under the direction of conductors including E. F. Svetlanov, K. P. Kondrashin, G. N. Rozhdestvensky, K. K. Ivanov, A. Yansons, L. Bernstein (USA), E. Ormandy (USA), C. Tsecky (Italy), V. Zavallish (Germany), N. del Mar (Great Britain), S. Bodo (France), F.P. Dekker (Canada), etc. Among the famous orchestras with played by the violinist - the Leningrad Orchestra of E. A. Mravinsky, the Bolshoi Symphony Orchestra of the All-Union Radio and Television , the London Symphony Orchestra , the BBC Symphony Orchestra , Ber Linna Philharmonic Orchestra , Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra (Amsterdam ), New York Symphony Orchestra , Washington State Orchestra, Philadelphia Symphony Orchestra , Tokyo Symphony Orchestra and other creative groups. For 25 years, the creative union of the musician with the USSR State Academic Symphony Orchestra continued . He gave concerts in world famous halls such as: the Great Hall of the Conservatory (Moscow), the Great Hall of the Leningrad Philharmonic, Carnegie Hall (New York), Lincoln Center (New York), Festival Hall (London), Albert Hall (London), Musicalferain (Vienna), Madison Square Garden(New York), Hall of the Berlin Philharmonic, Gewandhaus (Leipzig), Opera House (Sydney), and many others.\n\nHe has numerous records on phonograph records and CDs made by the companies: Melodia (Russia), EMI Elektrola (Great Britain), Ariola (Germany), Toshiba (Japan), Victor Company and Angel Records ( USA), \"Le Chant du Monde\" (France), etc.\n\nFrom 1965 to 1989 he taught at the [[Moscow Conservatory]] (since 1974 - head of the department of violin, since 1983 - professor). His students have included Aiman \u200b\u200bMusakhodzhaeva, Elena Denisova, and Evgeny Bushkov.\n\nKlimov has repeatedly participated in the jury of many international competitions including the P.I. Tchaikovsky in Moscow,  M. Long - J. Thibaud in Paris, N. Paganini in Genoa, W.A. Mozart in Salzburg, J. Sibelius in Helsinki , G. Kulenkampf in Cologne, as well as in competitions in Montreal and Tokyo, ect.\n\nSince 1989 he has been teaching at the Higher School of Music of Saarbr\u00fccken (Germany).\n\n==Awards and titles==\n*Laureate of the International Violin Competition at the III World Festival of Youth and Students in Berlin (1951)\n*Laureate of the International Violin Competition. M. Long and J. Thibaud in Paris (1955, 6th Prize)\n*Laureate of the violin competition named after J. Slavik and F. Ond\u0159icek as part of the Prague Spring International Music Festival (1956, 1st prize)\n*Laureate of the International Tchaikovsky Competition in Moscow (1958, 1st prize)\n*Honored Artist of the RSFSR (1962)\n*People's Artist of the RSFSR (1972)\n*People's Artist of the USSR (1989).\n\n==References==\n* The New Grove Dictionary of Music & Musicians - vol. X, pages 111-12.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050316010346/http://www.india.mid.ru/nf42.html Russia's Embassy in India]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Klimov, Valery}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian classical violinists]]\n[[Category:Male violinists]]\n[[Category:Soviet classical violinists]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical violinists]]\n[[Category:People's Artists of the USSR]]\n[[Category:Prize-winners of the International Tchaikovsky Competition]]\n[[Category:Long-Thibaud-Crespin Competition prize-winners]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical violinists]]\n", "text_old": "{{no footnotes|date=October 2008}}\n'''Valeri Klimov''' (born October 16, 1931) is a [[Russia]]n violinist.\n\n==Biography==\nKlimov was born in [[Kiev]] (then in the [[Soviet Union]], now in [[Ukraine]]). He began to study music under the guidance of his father - conductor and teacher [[Alexander Ignatievich Klimov]]. From the age of 7 he studied (with a break for evacuation in Stalingrad during the war) at the Odessa Music Boarding School for Gifted Children with [[Pyotr Stolyarsky]] (now called the [[School of Stolyarsky]] (for gifted children)), Starting in 1945, he studied with B.Z. Mordkovich. In 1949 he performed public concerts featuring repertoire by [[Alexander Glazunov]], [[W.A. Mozart]] and [[Felix Mendelssohn]]. There he met [[David Oistrakh]].\n\nIn 1951 he entered the Kiev Conservatory. P.I. Tchaikovsky (now the [[Petro Tchaikovsky National Music Academy of Ukraine]]), where he studied under B.S. Fishman. After a year of study, he was transferred to the [[Moscow Conservatory]] in the studio of [[David Oistrakh]] (graduated with honors in 1956, graduate school in 1959 under his tutelage).\n\nIn 1955, he took sixth place in what is now known as the [[Long\u2013Thibaud\u2013Crespin Competition]]. A year later, he became the winner of the J. Slavik and F. Ond\u0159icek violin competition, but his main success was brought by the 1st [[International Tchaikovsky Competition]] (1958), where he won the gold medal in the violin category.\n\nSince 1957, he has been a soloist of the Moscow Philharmonic Society. He performed in the USSR and abroad. He performed with the largest orchestras in the world under the direction of conductors including E. F. Svetlanov, K. P. Kondrashin, G. N. Rozhdestvensky, K. K. Ivanov, A. Yansons, L. Bernstein (USA), E. Ormandy (USA), C. Tsecky (Italy), V. Zavallish (Germany), N. del Mar (Great Britain), S. Bodo (France), F.P. Dekker (Canada), etc. Among the famous orchestras with played by the violinist - the Leningrad Orchestra of E. A. Mravinsky, the Bolshoi Symphony Orchestra of the All-Union Radio and Television , the London Symphony Orchestra , the BBC Symphony Orchestra , Ber Linna Philharmonic Orchestra , Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra (Amsterdam ), New York Symphony Orchestra , Washington State Orchestra, Philadelphia Symphony Orchestra , Tokyo Symphony Orchestra and other creative groups. For 25 years, the creative union of the musician with the USSR State Academic Symphony Orchestra continued . He gave concerts in world famous halls such as: the Great Hall of the Conservatory (Moscow), the Great Hall of the Leningrad Philharmonic, Carnegie Hall (New York), Lincoln Center (New York), Festival Hall (London), Albert Hall (London), Musicalferain (Vienna), Madison Square Garden(New York), Hall of the Berlin Philharmonic , Gewandhaus (Leipzig), Opera House (Sydney), and many others.\n\nHe has numerous records on phonograph records and CDs made by the companies: Melodia (Russia), EMI Elektrola (Great Britain), Ariola (Germany), Toshiba (Japan), Victor Company and Angel Records ( USA), \"Le Chant du Monde\" (France), etc.\n\nFrom 1965 to 1989 he taught at the [[Moscow Conservatory]] (since 1974 - head of the department of violin, since 1983 - professor). His students include Aiman \u200b\u200bMusakhodzhaeva, Elena Denisova, and Evgeny Bushkov.\n\nKlimov has repeatedly participated in the jury of many international competitions including the P.I. Tchaikovsky in Moscow,  M. Long - J. Thibaud in Paris, N. Paganini in Genoa, W.A. Mozart in Salzburg, J. Sibelius in Helsinki , G. Kulenkampf in Cologne, as well as in competitions in Montreal and Tokyo, ect.\n\nSince 1989 he has been teaching at the [[Higher School of Music of Saarbr\u00fccken]] (Germany).\n\n==Awards and titles==\n*Laureate of the International Violin Competition at the III World Festival of Youth and Students in Berlin (1951) [3]\n*Laureate of the International Violin Competition. M. Long and J. Thibaud in Paris (1955, 6th Prize)\n*Laureate of the violin competition named after J. Slavik and F. Ond\u0159icek as part of the Prague Spring International Music Festival (1956, 1st prize)\n*Laureate of the International Tchaikovsky Competition in Moscow (1958, 1st prize)\n*Honored Artist of the RSFSR (1962)\n*People's Artist of the RSFSR (1972)\n*People's Artist of the USSR (1989).\n\n==References==\n* The New Grove Dictionary of Music & Musicians - vol. X, pages 111-12.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050316010346/http://www.india.mid.ru/nf42.html Russia's Embassy in India]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Klimov, Valery}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian classical violinists]]\n[[Category:Male violinists]]\n[[Category:Soviet classical violinists]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical violinists]]\n[[Category:People's Artists of the USSR]]\n[[Category:Prize-winners of the International Tchaikovsky Competition]]\n[[Category:Long-Thibaud-Crespin Competition prize-winners]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical violinists]]\n\n\n{{Russia-classical-musician-stub}}\n{{ukraine-musician-stub}}\n{{violinist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "CTGvio20", "label": "safe", "comment": "This page should no longer be considered a stub.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valery_Klimov_(violinist)"}
